{
  "_dft": {
    "_doc": "Simple CPU wrapped with a full DFT layer — interview showcase.\n\n  CORE (unchanged single-cycle CPU):\n    PC → ROM → IR → CU → ALU ↔ REG_FILE_DP (RF) ↔ RAM, with a write-back MUX.\n\n  PRE-LOADED REGISTERS (no LI used — initialRegs seeds the RF):\n    R0=0  R1=5  R2=1  R3=0  R4=7  R5=3  R6=99  R7=0  R8..R15=0.\n\n  PROGRAM (8 instructions, no LI, exercises RF + RAM + branches):\n    0: ADD   R3,R3,R1       ; R3 += R1               (accumulator)\n    1: STORE R1,R5          ; mem[R5=3] = R1         (RAM write)\n    2: SUB   R1,R1,R2       ; R1 -= 1                (counter)\n    3: BNE   R1,R0,0        ; loop while R1 != 0     (4× TAKEN, 1× NOT-TAKEN)\n    4: LOAD  R7,R5          ; R7 = mem[3]            (RAM read into RF)\n    5: ADD   R3,R3,R7       ; R3 += R7\n    6: BEQ   R0,R6,0        ; 0==99 ? — NEVER TAKEN  (predictor mispredict)\n    7: HALT\n\n  EXECUTION HIGHLIGHTS (for the interviewer):\n    • RF changes: R1 walks 5→4→3→2→1→0; R3 accumulates 5,9,12,14,15,16; R7 loaded from RAM.\n    • RAM changes: addr 3 written successively with 5,4,3,2,1; last value read back into R7.\n    • Branch demo:\n        – BNE at PC=3 is taken 4 times, not-taken once → ideal for the 2-bit predictor\n          (it converges to 'Strongly Taken' and only mispredicts the final exit).\n        – BEQ at PC=6 is never taken; with default static-NT predictor this is a hit,\n          with a static-T or saturated 2-bit it would mispredict. Use BRANCH PREDICTOR\n          (PIP panel) to swap predictors and watch the hit/miss column flip.\n\n  DFT LAYER (added without altering the CPU's datapath):\n    1) SCAN CHAIN ON PC — 4 SCAN_FFs in a chain capture PC[3:0] when TE=0\n       (functional / capture) and shift the captured state out serially on\n       SCAN_OUT when TE=1 (shift). SCAN_IN provides the serial input.\n       Demonstrates IEEE-style internal scan: 'observe the PC without an oscilloscope'.\n\n    2) MISR SIGNATURE COMPACTOR — an 8-bit MISR taps the RF read-port-A bus\n       (the 'operand A' going into the ALU) every cycle and compacts a\n       running 'signature' of the program's execution (Fibonacci form,\n       polynomial taps [7,5,3,2]). SIG is the live signature register —\n       equivalent to a CRC over the test response. Tapping the RF output\n       (instead of the ALU output) keeps the MISR observable in the topo\n       sort without sitting inside the CU↔ALU feedback loop, while still\n       capturing every register read the program performs. Inject a stuck-at\n       fault on the RF/MISR path (DFT panel ➜ click a wire ➜ Stuck-at-0/1)\n       and SIG diverges from the fault-free value: classic 'observation\n       compression' for BIST.\n\n    3) BIST CONTROLLER — an FSM (IDLE → SETUP → RUN → COMPARE → DONE/FAIL)\n       that watches the MISR signature for runLength=24 cycles after START,\n       then COMPAREs against goldenSig and latches PASS or FAIL. Set goldenSig\n       to the fault-free signature you observe on a clean run, then inject a\n       fault and re-run: PASS → FAIL transition with no extra wiring.\n\n    4) LFSR PATTERN GENERATOR — a free-running 8-bit Fibonacci LFSR\n       (taps [7,5,4,3], maximal length 255) wired to LFSR_Q. Available as a\n       pseudo-random test-vector source for off-line ATPG / test-mode demos.\n\n  HOW TO RUN THE DEMO (interview script):\n    a) Hit RUN — watch the CPU execute. Open MEM to see RF + RAM evolve;\n       open PIP ➜ BRANCH PREDICTOR to see BNE's prediction record converge.\n    b) Open the DFT panel — note that the PC-scan chain is auto-detected,\n       and the BIST_CTRL state is reported live.\n    c) Capture the fault-free MISR signature into BIST.goldenSig\n       (DFT panel ➜ BIST ➜ ✎ ➜ 'capture live SIG').\n    d) RESET and pulse START — FSM advances IDLE → SETUP → RUN (24 cycles)\n       → COMPARE → DONE/PASS.\n    e) Right-click a wire near the ALU ➜ inject Stuck-at-0. RESET, START\n       again — same FSM run now ends in FAIL. You have just demonstrated\n       fault detection by signature analysis on a live CPU.\n    f) Set TE=1 and step a few clocks — PC bits shift out on SCAN_OUT;\n       set TE=0 to re-capture and resume functional operation."
  },
